<Base title="core-1337" description="the foundation for 1337 mode">
  <p><a href="/claude-1337/reference/">&larr; reference</a></p>

  <p>the foundation. makes claude operate the 1337 way.</p>

  <h2>install</h2>

  <pre><code>/plugin install core-1337@claude-1337</code></pre>

  <p><strong>install this first</strong>, then add domain skills.</p>

  <h2>what it does</h2>

  <p>at session start, injects a <strong>forced eval hook</strong> that requires claude to explicitly evaluate and activate skills before responding.</p>

  <h3>the forced eval pattern</h3>

  <p>three mandatory steps:</p>

  <ol>
    <li><strong>EVALUATE</strong> — for each skill in <code>&lt;available_skills&gt;</code>, state YES/NO with reason</li>
    <li><strong>ACTIVATE</strong> — call <code>Skill(name)</code> for each YES immediately</li>
    <li><strong>IMPLEMENT</strong> — only after activation, proceed with response</li>
  </ol>

  <p>this creates a commitment mechanism. claude can't skip to implementation without first showing its work.</p>

  <h3>plus 1337 standards</h3>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>decisions, not catalogs</strong> — THE answer backed by evidence</li>
    <li><strong>craftsmanship</strong> — gotchas > tutorials, leave code better</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>why forced eval?</h2>

  <p><a href="https://scottspence.com/posts/how-to-make-claude-code-skills-activate-reliably">scott spence's research</a> tested 200+ prompts and found three patterns:</p>

  <table>
    <tr>
      <th>pattern</th>
      <th>activation rate</th>
      <th>notes</th>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td>simple hook</td>
      <td>~20%</td>
      <td>passive suggestion, claude ignores it</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td>LLM eval</td>
      <td>~80%</td>
      <td>10% cheaper but can fail spectacularly</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>forced eval</strong></td>
      <td><strong>~84%</strong></td>
      <td>commitment mechanism, most reliable</td>
    </tr>
  </table>

  <p>core-1337 uses the forced eval pattern.</p>

